For me, Chris Brown’s case is a blunt reminder of how easy it is to fall prey to pattern-recognition, and how much harder it is to remain skeptical and wait for the evidence.

Redemption and forgiveness are essential components of a system of justice. The cognitive processes that kept us safe as hunter-gatherers are not made for, or very good at, rendering just verdicts in courtrooms.

If we assume Chris Brown is guilty of raping someone today because he beat up Rihanna in 2009, then we are repeatedly punishing him for beating up Rihanna instead of punishing him for what he did or did not do this time.
As a closing thought, the reason pattern-recognition often produces unjust conclusions is because they foreclose the possibility of redemption, growth, and change.

It also illustrates how so many of these abuse hoaxes we see rely on pattern-recognition in place of evidence. I’m sure I’m not the only one who read the initial allegations, saw “Chris Brown,” and assumed she probably had a case.

Chris Brown provides a stark reminder that truly terrible people are still sometimes innocent. I face this constantly in my line of work, where my clients often have prior records that prosecutors fight to introduce in court to gain the advantage of the smear.

But it is important to distinguish the choices we make in our everyday lives with the choices we make in courtrooms, where guilt or liability depends on proving the specific wrong that has been alleged.

These conclusions are well and good in everyday life, and they aren’t necessarily wrong, and you’re not a bad person if you decide someone’s history makes them a threat you’d rather not risk dealing with.

And, if his allegations are true, his accusers have specifically relied upon pattern-recognition in place of proof by coordinating their stories and the specific claims of wrongdoing to create the perception of a pattern, so that the accusations alone are seen as evidence.

These same dynamics are playing out in Marilyn Manson’s case, where his public persona is relied upon to argue he has an abusive character, and then relied upon to prove his guilt in the absence of any *objective* evidence that he did what his accusers claim.
Both sides use this reasoning. That Amber Heard was arrested for assaulting her ex-wife Tasya Van Ree proves that she is an abuser, and therefore probably abused Johnny Depp.

For example, that Johnny Depp’s history of trashing hotel rooms and that time he maybe kinda assaulted a paparazzo taking pictures of his pregnant wife proves he has a “violent” character – therefore he probably abused Amber Heard.
While rules of court are not rules for everyday life, I bring this up to shed light on some of the arguments we commonly see on social media about high-profile accusations against public figures.

Because of this risk, evidence of a person’s propensity to commit wrongful acts is universally banned in U.S. courtrooms. The federal rule, which is mirrored in many states, is ER 404(b).
https://t.co/NMTKGc1b99

But introducing the defendant’s past wrongdoing shortcuts those logical processes. Jurors naturally conclude, “If he did it before, he probably did it this time,” even if there isn’t strong evidence that he actually did it this time.

Simply put, in a legal case, a person is accused of committing a particular wrongful act. The fact that the person is a terrible person, or has committed other wrongful acts, doesn’t *logically* prove that they committed the charged act.

But, pattern-recognition can be extremely problematic in a courtroom. The same processes that allow us to identify threats also operate to encourage us to draw unjust conclusions based on faulty reasoning.

Thinking this way allows us to quickly react to stimuli and shortcuts “higher-level” logical processes to reach conclusions. It’s very helpful when you need to identify external threats, such as distinguishing a poisonous berry from an edible one.

Human brains evolved as pattern-recognition machines. We have an amazing ability to take new information, compare it to old information, and make predictions by organizing the new information within the framework of our pre-existing knowledge.
